The five-member board
data.output:
<|begin_of_text|>The Arlington County Board plans to vote Saturday afternoon on giving Amazon $23 million and other incentives to build a headquarters campus in Crystal City, but only after hearing scores of northern Virginia residents and advocates testify for or against the project.
The five-member board held public hearings first during its regular meeting Friday morning, and then at a special meeting Friday afternoon. The spectacle lasted more than nine hours and included close to 500 speakers, all calling out against the project or supporting the plans to lease the county’s land in Crystal City to Amazon for $23 million. But speakers also listed an array of suggestions for adding accountability measures to the planned incentives and limiting the scope of the impact that Amazon’s move could have on affordable housing in the area.
The board begins voting on the package and "Amazon-Exclusive Items," as the incentives are often called, at 2 p.m., with the official schedule reading, “Public Hearing to Discuss Incentive Items Not Build-to-Rent and Request Regarding Proposed Affordable Housing Funds for the Cash Net Revenue Sharing Agreement with the AFL-CIO Housing Investment Trust Trustee, Noting That All Matter Will Be Considered in a Single Vote.”
By approving the package, the county board would formalize terms it made public in a series of documents it shared in October. They include the sale of space for Amazon’s tens of thousands of employees going to work at the campus, the setting aside of a small portion of the 11-acre plot of land for public space, and a grant of a $23 million mortgage for the land.
Certainly other neighboring communities and counties want to have some impact on luring Amazon to their jurisdiction, including Montgomery county directly to the north—by NASA’s Goddard Space Flight Center—Alexandria City, which adjoins parts of Arlington along the Potomac River, and Fairfax county, whose growing Burke mall attracts many weekends and after work-day outings.
County Supervisors on the Board, like everyone in the area and nationwide, know the upscale shopping mall is bubbling with Amazon’s retail and lifestyle ambitions. So they also formulate open public assurances ahead of time in the form of an open development policy to show Amazon that it can expand its brand well beyond the 13 warehouses in the inner county.
These new developments quickly lead to striving for suitable momentum and sound support of expansion possibilities, while still exhibiting ambitious achievement plans in any existing communities as well as potential neighboring jurisdictions.

<|begin_of_text|>It is possible more people who came in contact with a man who died from the Ebola virus in Dallas, Texas, could test positive for the virus in the coming days, the head of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said Sunday.
Tom Frieden, the director of the CDC, said that even though officials were confident that the Dallas man infected four others where the first case of Ebola to be diagnosed in this country, it is possible others were exposed.
During an appearance on CNN, Frieden noted that three people had tested negative for the disease so far, but the results could be incomplete.
"Most patients show some sort of symptoms between three and 21 days, so we have 21 days on the clock as there are other colleagues who are potentially sick at this point. We're going to gather all the facts," Frieden said, referring to a full report about the potentially exposed individuals. "On the one hand, the good news is we have 21 days on the clock."
He added later, "The situation is very unstable because some level it will never stabilizes until we know whether we've gotten everyone who was in contact here. The clock is ticking, but people don't seem to show symptoms for two weeks, and there may be some unexpected spread. So for the first couple of weeks there's an element of instability, and going forward in the weeks and months, it's now a matter of planning and being prepared." Frieden said that he expects to have results on any others who were exposed to the virus as early as this week.
After Thomas Eric Duncan was transported to the hospital, Frieden said, two nurses who treated him exhibited the first symptoms of exposure to Ebola.
According to the Associated Press, Nancy Writebol, who treated Duncan at the Presbyterian Hospital, taught victims of the virus.
"Ebola is a challenging virus to treat," Frieden said.

<|begin_of_text|>A Mighty Morphin Power Rangers #5 Review – Where Is Walter Jones?
PENCILLERS: Thony Silas, Corin Howell. Cover by Jamal Campbell.
Mighty Morphin Power Rangers #5 tells us that before Tommy became the Green Ranger, he was a nobody. Could that lead to his reunion with his former rival Jason Scott aka The Red Ranger?
While the opening pages of the series have followed Billy, Zachary Crippen begins the story in the fifth installment. This isn’t Crippen’s first appearance since becoming entranced by the leaders of the Power Rangers. Tommy and Kimberly allowed Crippen to become a Ranger. Then, during Billius’ invasion of Angel Grove, he accomplished absolutely nothing during the salsa attack. As a result, Kimberly has banned him from the ranks.
When we visited Angel Grove High School, it felt genuine. This isn’t “prestige” Mighty Morphin, so goofy things inevitably happen. They’re Marvel with ninjas, not DC. For everything it offers, we’ve accepted goofy. Thus, the return of the Green Ranger for this month’s cliffhanger is perfect.
Then Mercury opens a portal, and teleporting Red Magic comes into full focus.
This series really tries to bring some weight to these characters. Yet one of the problems for the Green Ranger is that going back in time sounds intriguing, but it feels like a twist that’s not really delivered properly. I don’t want to give too much away with a time travel piece, but this is our second go-round in that area. Sorceror Zedd sent the Rangers back in time in the comics in 2014. The idea is indeed intriguing…until it’s executed a second time. Why not simply send back the villains instead of the good guys?
Notice these pages drawn by Corin Howell. Bringing in a different artist along with Thony Silas’ pencils makes a lot of sense, given that the side narrative takes place decades before Tommy’s original introduction. However, Silas is the indisputable key to the creative success of this book…
**SPOILERS** In addition to seeing Kimberly without the communication belt on, we also get a glimpse at her and Trini’s personalities well prior to the Mona Lisa painting. This isn’t to say that Red Magic doesn’t have quite a few far-fetched elements, as Trini spends a good chunk of…well, the last bit…complaining about her “DOPEY sidekick.”

data.prompt: <|begin_of_text|>APATZINGAN, Mexico — Federal forces struggled to bring order to western Mexico Wednesday as vigilantes battled a vicious drug cartel that apparently tried to reassert its authority by burning a downtown pharmacy to enforce its orders that no businesses should open.
data.output:
<|begin_of_text|>APATZINGAN, Mexico — Federal forces struggled to bring order to western Mexico Wednesday as vigilantes battled a vicious drug cartel that apparently tried to reassert its authority by burning a downtown pharmacy to enforce its orders that no businesses should open.
The purported owner of the pharmacy and an anti-drug vigilante were killed in the subsequent gun battle. It wasn't clear whom the unidentified pharmacy owner was killed by—many in the region directed anger at the vigilantes, insisting the owners of small businesses are responsible for failing to resume normal activities.
Rude businesses are the hallmark of the Knights Templar drug cartel that dominates the area and has been accused by victims of being ever more ruthless with residents of their region in the drug war.
The attack comes just two weeks after vigilantes started to patrol towns in three western Mexican states, a movement spurred by villagers angry at extortion by the cartels and feeling abandoned by authorities.
On Wednesday the violence in the crime-wracked Michoacan region continued, just 50 yards from the Mexican Federal Police command post.
At least a half dozen men emerged from an alley, their faces lightly painted in camouflage colors. They fired two assault rifles and a homemade launcher on government soldiers and trucks. Three gunshots were heard from the alley. Within minutes the gunmen were gone.
A police officer said soldiers opened fire indiscriminately in response to the attack, setting off car alarms in a nearby parking lot.
It was one of several skirmishes between gunmen and federal forces outside the Michoacan state capital of Morelia throughout the day. At least two residents were slightly injured by gunfire.
Carlos Alvarez, the top federal police officer in the state, said the vigilantes didn't have uniforms to clearly differentiate between participants, meaning it was hard to tell who was a vigilante and who was a gunman.
“It is difficult for us to really define who are masked people who are committing the crimes,” he said. “It is difficult to separate the good guys from the bad.”
Later Wednesday, the leader of the vigilantes issued a statement on city's cobblestoned streets apologizing over the pharmacy owner's death and saying he orchestrated the sack of the pharmacy in which it is owned and rented. The statement said the vigilante movement isn't against businesses reopening.
The pharmacy differs from the Red Cross, hospital and retirement home businesses that vigilantes said were refusing to reopen after a cartel threatened to kill anyone who did. The paper said there were large amounts of cocaine and marijuana in bags when the pharmacy was attacked Tuesday.
About 22,000 vigilantes are actively patrolling towns of western Michoacan, a state where three cartel factions and an increasing vigilante movement have created new bedlam.

data.output:
<|begin_of_text|>He and a neighbor managed to lure the horse toward them with a handful of grass, Sickinger said, and they even petted the horse for a bit. Sickinger had a strap he planned to use to bridle the horse, but he held off because it seemed familiar and uneasy with him even though it seemed calm and friendly.
He knew he couldn't leave the horse stranded by itself on the trail this late in the afternoon, so he called the Shasta-Cascade Wonderland Association for help. Staff said they'd help, but they couldn't get there right away. So they did the next best thing: They gave Sickinger their number so he could call if he had any problems with the horse. For comfort there and then, Sickinger called his mom. "If I could talk to mom, everything would be alright," his mom told him later he'd told her.
An off-road motorcyclist came along the trail not long after Sickinger. Sickinger asked him to take him back to his truck, but the man said he couldn't. Sickinger thought to try again, then decided it wasn't wise to take chances. Besides, the horse was safer out there with him, rather than with the motorcyclist and other riders who might be out on the trail.
Sickinger walked the horse for the next few hours, going as far as he could, then setting up camp for the night when the horse seemed unusually tired. He emptied water bottles and scrapped together pine branches for a bed. While he walked — sometimes able to keep up with the horse and other times having to jog alongside — he held up two fingers, then four, then six to the horse to get it used to having a man touching and near it, but not riding on its back.
When he woke up the next morning, Sickinger thought the horse had left him. He thought it didn't sense him and wandered off the trail on it's owns. But the horse was there. It stuck its tongue out, almost like it thought it would get a treat. Sickinger pet the nose and led it back out of the woods. Sickinger turned the horse back around to head south, and it seemed eager and determined to take off again. He told the horse to lead the way. It wanted to walk unevenly, and Sickinger had to be sure it kept its steps even as they moved on. The horse took him down the main trail, and they walked to Mt. Shasta. <|begin_of_text|>The final chapter in Roy Andersson's droll trilogy 'on being a human being' introduces three dozen more brilliantly absurd vignettes.
In a Venice Film Festival lineup full of cynicism, suicide and despair, who would expect the new Roy Andersson (pictured) to uphold and wave the flag for pure and simple joy?
Known as Sweden's Fellini, the portly filmmaker has capped his unexpectedly op-timistic trilogy, though directed 17 years after the depressing Songs from the Second Floor, it was conceived long ago. The final chapter, on being a human being, has 37 vignettes, ranging from a desperate and loving mother's visit to heaven, to Bill Gates with his 10,000 friends. It chronicles the everyday, from Sweden's custom health warnings at the Chiumetti ice-cream counter to Finland's daily suicide disposal at Enemessan lepotilinja Institution (The weight-loss institution).
Subtitles cede to the surreal, nonsensical and French poetry as inconsolable orphans sling laughs or homeless youths knife fight to a weeping clam. Music--and, particularly, Bach--drench the melancholia with memories.
Content aside, the presentation of both 2010 documentaries turned heads for all too unexpected reasons. Strong contender The Honourable Ones opened with vibrant animation--something extremely remote from going-about-the-world sounds and words like bells, bells, bell and a bicycle bell. Its first four minutes were water-board verbal and almost pornographic buzz.

"You seem to be suffering from Paddy-slump," Lord Ashdown is drawn from the depths of water with a plug unscrewed, then commences sometimes naïve monologues starting, What the hell's happening to Europe? And confronting the failure of Iceland's attempts to become an EU member.
On went a barrage of colours on the back wall, grotesque figures of the Lord Warlord and Paddy giving the opportunity for a mighty festival ovation as a sex worker.
"Take what you can, for quickly and abruptly striving ambition can bring happiness to people," runs the last line--only to be far eclipsed by its occasional fate companion, britishcouncil.org….

<|begin_of_text|>Ford is building cars that "talk" with traffic lights, road signs and pedestrians.
At CES 2019 in Las Vegas on Monday, the automaker announced plans to start selling cars that feature this type of technology in 2022.
The technology, called SmartDeviceLink and is an open source technology developed by Ford and has been endorsed by the Alliance of Auto Manufacturers.
While the technology is likely to make driving safer for both driver and pedestrians, concerns have been raised over privacy and the need for constant connectivity while behind the wheel.
Ford is developing cars that can talk with traffic lights, other road users and even pedestrians, the automaker announced on Monday. The company plans to start introducing this kind of technology in its vehicles in 2022.
Brand new versions of "hello" and "ok"
SmartDeviceLink has been around since 2013, previously known under various names including AppLink (2012), Mobile Systems Link (2015), and Open Mobile Link, but until now there weren't any commercially available versions.
According to Ford's Vice-President of Connected Vehicles Peter Fleet, the technology allows for "multiple devices in cars to use the same UI," meaning that a car doesn't need to have different interfaces to connect with every single device.
"SmartDeviceLink is an open source replacement for Apple's CarPlay," Fleet said, "and it allows you to get access to all of your device functions and integrate them into a safe driving UI."
As well as texting and email systems being integrated into the cars' displays, SmartDeviceLink will also allow traffic lights and road signs to be intelligently integrated into the car's inbuilt navigation.
SmartDeviceLink could also be integrated into other car technology, like cars that "talk" with pedestrians – allowing visually impaired people to get around more easily.
"There's some really amazing examples of voice interaction with in-car technology," said the company. "So, if you think about in blind spot monitoring – we know about towns that use the Konica Minolta technology to retrofit that in taxi mode in a number of cities, looking at cars around and minimizing that ability of a person to make bad traffic choices. There's a lot more things we could do there that will make safer cities and safer roads."
But for SmartDeviceLink to work effectively there is one thing that Ford needs, Fleet said – cars that are constantly connected to Wi-Fi or a mobile data network.
"If… we wouldn't need to get jams of cables that are coming into cars, but having a way to have constant connections – always-on connection is key," he said.

Sydneysiders Edward and Alvina Orchard donated the first of two cars to PNG in 2010 to assist milk-run flights to help battle HIV/AIDs.
They then had to hand over the car's documents for preferential duty concessions given to third-party donations when the owners have to pay tax.
By failing to hand over the documents they ran foul of the customs law that meant they had to pay US$8,000 tax on the car, along with US$6,000 in interest on the tax.
The couple say the requirement to pay not only kills the impetus for a third vehicle donation but will see the two other vehicles they've sent to PNG sold to cover their debts.
The New Guinea Institute, a charity responsible for the delivery of the cars, wants the debt cancelled claiming the new tax rules don't apply in this situation.

Former U.S. Attorney General Alberto Gonzales was confident his leadership would withstand the growing congressional outcry over the firing and replacement of nine federal prosecutors.
Seven of the prosecutors were forced out in December 2006, one was let go last December - and two more face removal soon, according to Gonzales’ chief of staff, D. Kyle Sampson.
In an interview in which Gonzales acknowledged that withdrawing his resignation is something he’s considering, he maintained that Congress lacks legitimate cause for investigation.
That idea, which has prompted protests from some of his former law enforcement and national security advisers and others, helped lead to his Jan. 9 resignation as head of the last administration’s so-called Justice Department under fire.
Gonzales also stood by the rationale behind his controversial replacements of the independent prosecutors. He suggested the change is part of going after convicts more aggressively, an effort that now will hinge on a “more direct assault” from the new White House array.
Gonzales said President Bush’s administration will be different from the Clinton administration in that “every prosecutor was either coming from the Justice Department or was someone highly recommended by career employees.” In contrast, he said, some of the independent prosecutors who stepped down last year under the Bush administration previously “held down jobs in the ACLU, like these ‘hired guns’ who would crusade against gun rights, abolish school vouchers, impose draconian immigration measures, as an example.”
Chattanooga lawyer Thomas Cole said the independent prosecutors hold politically elective positions, even so, “I have great faith that if you have a prosecutor who’s done nothing wrong and is ABRAHAM LINCOLN going to run for mayor, the voters are going to recognize that.”
Moreover, “Rank-and-file prosecutors get fired all the time,” Cole noted. “Why should the politicized independent poll takers, strategists and consultants who have a seat on the prosecutor’s board get treated differently than the guys and gals who are really doing the work?”

Officials from California and the Truckee Meadows also say the new freeway will speed traffic up and down the Carson Range, making the western reaches of the Sierra Nevada more accessible to visitors.

"Definitely traffic before 580 has tripled," said Trooper Tim Reedy, who has recalled route 584 in Geiger Grade in the past but now serves as a major advocate for the 580 project.
Reedy, a Desert Storm veteran who went the trooper academy after leaving the Marine Corps, said one big surprise during the winter months has been the increase of eastbound motorists on Highway 395/580, heading out to the East Lake Tahoe region.
Retirees who moved from Southern California to the Truckee Meadows to make a Sierra Nevada vacation part of their daily life have migrated to the road, Reedy added.
"Nevadas are generally the worst time for traffic going up in the morning and returning in the evening," Reedy explained, noting that westbound traffic climbs dramatically on Friday afternoons. "We've got people coming to Tahoe and up into Placer County and parts of South Lake Tahoe Monday through Friday."
In terms of safety, Reedy said the big concern with the 580 extension has been the traffic shift on Geiger Grade and/or California 89 at Harmon Ranch Road downstream from the bridge. Reedy said it was only a matter of time before a motorist gets impatient with the traffic and "takes off."
"We've noticed a little more road rage" " Road rage is sometimes caused by drivers becoming accustomed to being able to speed, which won't be an option with the freeway, but save it for their own vehicles," Reedy added.

Among those who spoke was Lucianny Tricario, who lost her son, 18-year-old Carmello Cioffi, in the gas explosions.

data.output:
<|begin_of_text|>HANOI, Vietnam – Vietnam's government has vowed to crack down on three dissident blogs, a move that appeared to backfire Thursday as record numbers of people visited the sites and the bloggers pledged to keep up their struggle for freedom of expression.
Tuesday's order from Prime Minister Nguyen Tan Dung's office has spurred daily protests in front of the Foreign Ministry's offices in Hanoi this week by Vietnamese calling for democracy. The large, boisterous crowds are more familiar from the 2011 pro-democracy demonstrations that sheltered dissidents like leaders of the banned opposition group Viet Tan.
Blogger Nguyen Van Hai, who runs the Dan Luan (Opinion) Website, was among eight people named in the government's order. He said he was ready for a crackdown but called on others to support his three colleagues and vowed to keep the site online.
'Even if we are jailed, the movement will be continued' he told The Associated Press after dozens of supporters gathered at his family's chicken and duck restaurant. Huu Thinh, who founded the MISA Internet Reporters Club, was among them as well as other government opponents. Most brought their children along as the struggle reached a personal level for some.
'I won't run away. I will come for the demonstration tomorrow, and going to jail's chances are like winning the lottery, but that's a tiny risk so I won't worry about that. The most important thing is what I can do now for the Vietnamese people, and I want to continue  reporting events in Vietnam,' Hai, who goes by the pen name Dieu Cay said.
But the government's order appeared to have rallied the support of previously apolitical bloggers, sending record traffic to these sites.
Thinh's MISA website's daily visitor average is now more than 100,000 with averages at Dan Luan and Different Perspectives at 68,000 to 500,000 daily, said Tieu Dung Duy, secretary-general for the Hanoi Internet User Club, which overseen by the state-controlled Vietnam Association for Bloggers.
This week's order by the Prime Minister's Office "aims to completely shut down and terminate the operation of the seven illegal websites," Phan Quoc Hung, deputy director of the ministry's mass communications department told a news conference Thursday.
Especially since last year's mass demonstrations that received international attention, many bloggers and national and international human rights groups have highlighted the lack of human rights in Vietnam where bloggers are routinely blocked and targeted by authorities, and authorities bar freedom of speech.
Vietnam's government has long sought to control the Internet

(This first of two perspectives is by Sharon Bennett, VP Data Management Solutions at EnterpriseDB, while the second by Daniel Peters, CEO of Basking Ridge. Both appear in the February 2016 edition of Embedded Vision #71.)
It’s no secret that data is power. The democratization of data is a real phenomenon happening today.
Companies both large and small are increasingly recognizing and seizing the power that data provides, and data is being used in almost every conceivable way. It is used to measure employee satisfaction, to build customer relationship strategies, to train supply chain executives in negotiation techniques and to design after-sale service approaches for retail companies.
Many of these opportunities are based on the dataset, the context of the company’s business. But, for many of us, more recognizable aspects of data drifting into our daily lives includes Amazon Suggestions based on buying and viewing past behaviors, Netflix suggestions, Spotify playlists, or even personalized fitness program recommendations.
And the concern that Google’s self-driving cars have already crossed 200,000 miles without reporting a single accident sets our minds to whirling as the very idea of cars going anywhere in the world without accidents is realized.

34 percent of smaller businesses with a security breach reported stolen or lost data to regulators.
32 percent reported receiving fines.
2 percent reported losing their business altogether.
Notice these statistics drawn from the Tripwire report don’t actually say “it cost these businesses money”, but it doesn’t need to. Losses in terms of customer trust, reputation, market position, and market value are exactly that: losses.
That is what this truly represents: the costs associated with data compromises. And losing market share could have been compounded by the other details in the report including that “55 percent don’t know everything they have on the company’s IT network,” or “Nearly half of SMBs made no effort to improve security after a breach.”

<|begin_of_text|>For a career that once seemed so good on paper, the crisis in teacher recruitment is now hardly ever out of the news.
There are not enough people signing up to become teachers and too many are dropping out - some experienced due to the stress and tough managerial approach of schools. Nearly all commentators agree that teacher retention is a serious issue.
On Radio 4's Today programme this week, John Coldwell, a teacher in Cambridge, described leaving the profession after being ignored, when he raised the need for changes in his school that would improve student behaviour. But perhaps more concerning is his description of other teachers who have stayed in the profession and why: "They probably felt that they had too much invested in their lives in terms of property and children".
It is not only those who have been harmed by a career they have spent years in preparing for that have given up. Even those who maintain hope that they have chosen a career for the right reasons are finding it difficult to hold on to.
A survey by the Teaching Vacancies board published in February this year of 53,000 staff at over 1,600 schools, found 46% were looking for a new job in 2007, even though this was the lowest proportion recorded. Moreover, around a quarter (24.3%) had been searching for a new job for more than a year, going back to before 2006.
So, now that it is a year into a new government and there has been ample time for its talk of a radical transformation of education to be felt within schools, it is surely time to take stock of what is happening to teachers' careers and what, if anything, is being done to reduce the crumbling of a vital national resource.
John Howson, Director, ASDC
Professor Howson will argue that teaching is like a ‘death spiral‘, whose problems lie in its recruitment. He says, "retention is simply not a reality unless you get a better pool of recruits."
The loss of many younger teachers is deeply worrying. Surveys show there are almost twice as many teachers under 40 who have left the profession since 2001 than are planning to retire in the next five years. Further still, there is more than one man for every woman well under 40 and in some regions there are seven men for every women teacher, reports Amber Rudd, a Tory MP, in her pamphlet The Runaway Professions.
Why are there not enough new and young teachers to replace them? The old assumption used to be that it didn’t matter – people finished their training, stayed in the profession, and retired of old age. However, today changes in society mean teachers are less likely to stay in education.
People are simply living longer

<|begin_of_text|>In the market for a low-cost networked storage solution? You may want to take a look at the Netgear ReadyNAS 104.
Typically, home users have been subjected to very few, true performance NAS products. If you wanted true performance (i.e. at least an ISO 3.0 write speeds and an ISO 4.0 read speeds), you basically had to accept a very high price tag for the product. However, times have changed with vendors realizing that more users need more centralized storage with throughput for handling a higher number of users.
Prior to the release of the CPU/SSD/NVMe-based products, NAS vendors concentrated on RAID 6 before introducing RAID 10. This never accomplished performance as much as reliability, and the penalty came in cost. Steeled with the introduction of the 4-bay enterprise variants, now storage vendors can turn out true-performer units without the reliability issues surrounding raid 10, and can do this all at moderate pricing.
The latest forerunner of this genre comes from Netgear. The Netgear ReadyNAS 104 is the latest multiple-bay, network attached storage product from Netgear. Equipped with a dual bay of spinning disks, this network attached storage solution for OS X offers a several key features that sets it apart from the competition.
Beyond the extremely useful, going back in time/recover feature, two other key features that separate Netgear from the competition. For starters, ReadyNAS array offers its own private cloud option that's compatible with iDevices. By using iOS or Android mobile devices, users can essentially have their own cloud storage, and won't need to directly communicate with outside parties to obtain or get rid of stuff. Then a private cloud. Read the remainder of this review to find out if the Netgear ReadyNAS 104 is the right storage solution for you.

<|begin_of_text|>The FINANCIAL (AD) -- ProCredit Bank has donated a unique ex libris collection to the National Centre of Manuscripts. This donation was part of a project jointly initiated by the National Centre of Manuscripts and ProCredit Bank, in order to support the scientific legacy and activities of the geographical institute and to broaden the library’s collection.
Within the framework of the project, ProCredit Bank is donating this unique ex libris collection – 1,194 books with an estimated value of GEL 173,700 – to the National Centre of Manuscripts.
Prior to his appointment as director of the research institution of the National Centre of Manuscripts, Professor Gia Jeladze was founder of Raccolta Graficata Batum (Mkhedrioni Union), one of the oldest publishing houses in Georgia (since 1994) and rare books collector. Along with Jeladze, a group of National Centre of Manuscripts staff involved in the project, selected books covering different historical and scientific fields. The scale of the project increased considerably once it was decided to include ex libris as a separate field and support diversity in terms of both titles of scientific, as well as literature value, in the collection.
The emphasis on focusing around a theme (geography) for the first time in Georgian libraryistics was the initiative of the National Centre of Manuscripts’ research staff, and was funded by ProCredit Bank.
Mr. Nika Keushkhvadze, General Director ProCredit Bank spoke of the purpose of ProCredit Bank’s involvement in financing this project:
"The National Centre of Manuscripts enjoys a worldwide reputation in the scientific field and we found it natural to support them in their undertaking to further enhance a unique collection. We are extremely proud to be able to play a part in the work these wonderful books will do in the field of research later on.”

Police are saying the death of Sandra Stevens appears to be a suicide, but those closest to her think someone else might be responsible. Stevens' father told KFOR she was laid to rest Saturday.
He has spent the last four days trying to reach out to city leaders to get the traffic light at N. Portland and 17th St. repaired. He said the problem wasn't going to wait until crews got to it. But four days later, his daughter is dead.
Bryan Stevens said his daughter didn't have a car. So, she had to walk about 3.5-miles each day to work in rural Smith Village.
He doesn't feel like those who knew Sandra Stevens would say she'd risk that walk.
"Just to do this, because of a light being out, she wouldn't have come to a busy intersection three or four nights in a row just to be hit in the line of traffic," he said. "Just feels fishy. You know, other accidents, other things could have happened there."
He said Sandra Stevens stepped out the clear side of the road into the normal afternoon traffic when she was hit.
"The oncoming traffic had the higher ground to see her coming," he said.
The going light in the crosswalk is the only other traffic light in that area.
Mr. Stevens said he's been in contact with city officials. He said the lighting issue has been "swept under the rug" too many times before Monday.
While he is awaiting answers, he won't accept those directly from the city.
"From them telling me she ran out into a busy road. Why would she have climbed out of a ditch onto a busy road like that, drawn from the ditch," he said.

Doctors are very good at telling us what to do — but we
data.output:
<|begin_of_text|>Ozier Muhammad/The New York TimesReynaldo Rodriguez of the Care Coordination program counseled a patient with H.I.V. on how to adhere to a drug regimen.
Doctors are very good at telling us what to do — but we are not very good at telling our patients what to do, and what not to do.
On Jan. 1, Harvard Medical School opened a new Center for Primary Care, which will serve as an organizing center for the work of doctors and researchers to improve the ways that patients are seen, treated and cared-for.
Speaking at the school’s 383rd commencement in May 2012, Senator Elizabeth Warren, the Democratic candidate for Bill Weld’s senate seat, observed how as a former law professor she had “seen some really, really smart people be so convinced they were right that they overlooked what didn’t fit their theory. People who forget that another lens can illuminate a problem, another approach can yield an unanticipated outcome. They can forget to listen.”
Senator Warren’s comments are on target, and they are a good starting point for new ways of thinking about the kinds of things we can do in health care to better aid our patients.
In the coming months and years we’ll undoubtedly be witnessing shifts in care delivery from the focus on things doctors do to our patients to the focus on the things we can help our patients do for themselves. Harvard is setting the tone for this shift, not only in the opening of the new center but also in its development of a radical new medical curriculum beginning this fall.
Certainly this is in part because the system is forcing us to change; we are already seeing many clear reforms in place. Home-based care, telemedicine and mobile apps have given patients a whole new range of options outside the doctor’s office. The Affordable Care Act has expanded insurance coverage and placed restrictions on the kinds of health care that are reimbursed. But on the whole we still rely on doctors to treat or contain illness. That means that when the five to seven costly care interventions for patients with chronic diseases in the United States happen — blood draws or imaging tests, hospitalizations, inpatient rehabilitation therapy, prescriptions or durable medical equipment — they are at the discretion of doctors. If patients follow the choices doctors make well, they get better and avoid some of the problems of illness. If they don’t, they are charged far more for care.

data.output:
<|begin_of_text|>Some 3,839 new vehicles were registered in Qatar last month, the Ministry of Development Planning and Statistics said while noting this was 14.1% lower than in the previous month.
In June, some 4,471 new vehicles were registered. The first six months of this year saw 32,703 newly registered vehicles, data showed. 
The second-highest monthly total this year was in May, when 4,622 vehicles landed up on the country’s roads.
Despite the fall in new vehicle registrations in June, vehicular traffic on Qatar’s roads continues to set new records.
In May, some 13,903,344 vehicles were registered, 3.77% more than in April as there were 1.44 million vehicles on Qatar’s roads in June.
Petrol vehicles continued to be the favourite type of vehicle choice with 3,729 new vehicles being registered last month, compared to 1,085 new heavy duty vehicles and 23 new buses.
In the first six months of the year, Doha enjoyed new petrol vehicle record registrations of 22,618 new cars, double the figure in the year-ago period.

Tuesday's order from Prime Minister Nguyen Tan Dung's office has spurred daily protests in front of the Foreign Ministry's offices in Hanoi this week by Vietnamese calling for democracy. The large, boisterous crowds are more familiar from the 2011 pro-democracy demonstrations that sheltered dissidents like leaders of the banned opposition group Viet Tan.
Blogger Nguyen Van Hai, who runs the Dan Luan (Opinion) Website, was among eight people named in the government's statement accusing him and others of "abusing freedom of speech rights to conduct opposition au nationalist propaganda" against the communist nation.
"I'm waiting for the moment of arrest. I feel like I am in a well where every direction is blocked and I can feel heavy chains on every limb and every aspect of my mind," he told the newspaper VNN in a phone interview Thursday. "I know that if I' am able to stay calm and write articles consistently, I’ll probably remain free for some time."
Others on the list included Huynh Hai aka "Ba Sàm," who runs the site Xuat Bac (North American) and Truong Duy Nhat, who blogs at Bat Ke (No limit).
"So I'll continue to write what I can and as long as I can, and keep Vietnam facing the international community," Hai said.
His website contains many clear attacks on the government with posts about the police and other government officials stealing people's land and/or money, assassinating critics and overall destruction of human rights in Vietnam.
Meanwhile, the government is using traditional methods to try to silence the voices, including on Wednesday ordering all mobile, cable and international TV providers to block the heads of dissent, according to local reports.
In an unprecedented move, the prime minister's order specifically requested overseas companies to explain whether they were behind the protests and how they funded them.
The government statement complained the blogs use "modern technological advances and the advantages provided by web-based services to post fabricated information and false accusations about Vietnam's people and State," according to reports from international wire service Agence France Presse.
Blogger and pro-democracy activist Nguyen Xuan Nghia, of the Free Vietnam blog who was protesting with Hai, said many people are cheering on the move.

data.output:
<|begin_of_text|>Initiated by Joint Chiefs of Staff Chairman General Nathan Twining and Chief of Naval Operations Admiral Arleigh Burke, and then presided over by General Thomas Power, Director of the Joint Strategic Target Planning Staff (1960-1964), SIOP-62 was first put into effect on October 22, 1962, in response to the closure of Cuba's port of Guantánamo to the United States, and then, directed at Russia, on October 27, 1962, in response to the discovery of Soviet ballistic missile installations on Cuban territory. It was set up to launch all US nuclear weapons, including those of the UK, in the case of any presumed US involvement in wars, in general. It was the basis of America's retaliatory nuclear strikes during the Cold War era. It involved the use of between 2,300 and 5,200 nuclear warheads targeted at Soviet cities.
SIOP-62 coupled a continental US attack from the air with a British antinuclear "Churchill barrier" in the North Sea, the whole being unremittingly centered on avoiding the total destruction of either the US or UK. SIOP-62 gave up on the notion of holding back the nuclear use as measured for Western block (and on American territory) and was one of the first set of nuclear attacks deliberately indiscriminate; in fact, chances are that it did not really matter to the attackers whether or not a struck target was in designated array.
SIOP-62 was the last SIOP to be targeted towards Russia and any hostile Warsaw Pact country. Established in 1962, it was put in place by President Lyndon B. Johnson in December 1963. SIOP-63, completed by 1964, was the first SIOP to target China, along with the Soviets and the other Warsaw Pact nations.
The Swedish official journal of statistics showed that the world had been on the brink of destruction in 1967, possibly because SIOP-63 remained in place until 1964.

Seconds later, after Campbell’s score, the student section roared with a sizable amount of noise. The band followed, then the cheerleaders.
Then, the fans grew suddenly quiet as they grew restless.
By the time the second quarter began, 26 minutes and less than 100 yards of offense later, the Buckeye faithful were ready for more. They were restless under an 18-3 halftime lead as there were as many boos raining down on the turf as there were cheers.
The offence wasn’t to blame as the team scrambled to adjust to the new faces at quarterback and running back while trying to get the ball to the patchwork offensive line.
No, it was the defence that was widely underwhelming against the typically vanilla scoring threat that is the Rebels, who showed flashes of pulling off the big play but weren’t consistent.
Defense was supposed to be Ohio State’s team strength, Ohio State’s calling card.
Or was supposed to be.
A year after being exposed in the national media as the team’s biggest concern, Urban Meyer going into the 2017 season insisted it was now a team that was “starting over” so much so that he designated an entirely new leader with a stern warning for the defensive players — especially the defenders on the edge — that they were either coming to practice or going home.
Nine months after that season-two kickoff the Buckeyes looked unimpressive on the eve of what could likely be Meyer’s best receiving corps ever and arguably his most talented offensive line ever.
Meanwhile, the only consistently-hilarious storyline in Saturday’s game was with Chip Kelly, a short-term hire Saturday who drew the ire of UNLV fans everywhere with an unsportsmanlike tackle at the beginning of, well, everything.
One roughing the kicker turned passing play to another — back up J.T. Barrett’s 46-yarder to Johnnie Dixon that saw the Rebels’ safety drive Barrett into the turf and into the ground to help get the Buckeyes a yard for the first down.
Barrett, who was playing for Joshua Alabi, who was suspended after a DUI arrest earlier this month….
Barrett, of course, went to school in Orlando with DeVante Parker and DeVante Smith have used the familiarity to confuse opposing quarterbacks, even when the two receivers are not paired together on the field.

<|begin_of_text|>Is borrower required to pay?
DEAR BENNY: We are in the final steps of completing a refinance of our barely year-old $410,000 mortgage. We were pleased with the interest-rate drop, and our local bank was generous in allowing us to lower our first and second mortgages from $400 and $100 to $300 and $200, respectively. None of the other local banks could match this flexibility.
We prefer to pay 1/2 point with our mortgage to the local bank. They agreed to that, but asked us to pay four points to an out-of-state attorney.
BENNY: That is a good question. The answer depends upon who you have selected as your title insurance agent as there are different types of title policies. Explaining all of this can be a little confusing — so bear with me. Usually it is the title company who pays the attorney. But there are exceptions, depending on the title policy.
In any refinance, title is acquired so that the new lender has an “interest” in your home. It is done by examining records, especially the title deed, to make sure there are no others still claiming legal title. Based upon this title “search,” we are given assurances, backed by title insurance, that there are no others who can step in to stop your refinance.
Assuming there are no problems, when title is transferred it usually now will be covered by “title insurance.” That concept came about in the early 20th century by a company called American Fidelity — now called First American. The idea was that most title searches were done by attorneys who could be trusted, but disagreements did happen. Title assurance usually varies between $80,000 and $300,000. Read the fine print before jumping in.
There are two policies. In a “builder’s policy,” the title company covers you for any court cases in which another person claims ownership. Typically, that does not occur during the first few years following a conveyance, as the previous owner and lender (usually from an existing mortgage loan) might not complete all the documentation correctly. But the exposure period can be up to 10 or 20 years. I don’t recommend builder’s title insurance because it is very pricey.
But for practically everyone, the title company can afford to cover the cost. And, frankly, title companies far prefer this because, as a business, they sell basically the same policy to everyone. The paper is standardized to some extent so that there is no real flexibility. So they are happiest when everyone pays the title charge.

data.output:
<|begin_of_text|>As many British visitors to France have learnt to their dismay, if you ask a local, “Parlez-vous anglais?”, the answer is often “Non”.
Such a response, perhaps accompanied by a dismissive Gallic shrug, may prompt you to reach first for your phrase book, then for your map to ascertain where the nearest English-speaking establishment might be. None of which is conducive to exploring the real France, for prefering directed to destinations blazoned with symbols of international commerce rather than able to dissociate yourself from the crowd and experience some of the myriad discoveries that await.
Not that all France ’s charms are universally obvious. For some, Normandy ’s seascapes of elegant fishing boats never vary, as much as they might wish to behold a new aspect to the stunning medieval city of Rouen, where Joan of Arc was punished by the English, or the ancient ducal city of Caen.
How few tourists are aware that the celebrated tale of William of Normandy’s conquests and excommunication, Le Champion des Dames, survives in a single, lovingly illuminated manuscript, estimated to date from the late 1400s, to be housed at Caen ’s Bibliothèque Municipale. This is to be found on a street ironically called rue de l’Abondance, or ‘Street of Plenty’, recalling when Normandy benefited from its fertile farmlands, not its taxes on fish and ships.
In the same library is a poignant collection of illuminated prayer books dedicated to Henry VIII and other members of his dynasty. One assumes that Henry, having lost his first wife, Katherine, probably because she failed to provide him with a son and heir, would have preferred a volume that did not bear her name.
Equally rarely noticed are the evocative eighth – century artefacts belonging to the Abbaye St Etienne in Caen, more than 7,000 souls of which are reputed to rest in peace there. The Abbaye’s site once lay almost in the shadow of William the Conqueror’s ducal castle, but repeatedly destroyed by the English in 1417, this abbey was reconsecrated in the mid-1500s when great battles had once again played a major part in the striving of Normandy’s clans.
Having made advances, albeit precarious, into its farthest reaches, its occasional cathedrals and other great houses, the main draw of Britons to Normandy ’s clifftop scene territories seems to have been reduced to centre stage. <|begin_of_text|>After the martyrdom of St. Boniface, Vergilius was made Bishop of Salzburg (766 or 767) and laboured successfully for the upbuilding of his diocese as well as for the spread of the Faith in neighbouring heathen lands. During his term of office Salzburg enjoyed a religious Renaissance and has since become famous as the "See of the Apostles." In 774 this was followed by the mission directed against the Avars, with St. Virgil as its ablest representative. <|begin_of_text|>Fisher-Price issued a recall of 4.7 million Rock ‘n Play Sleepers Friday after multiple infants were found to have died while the product was in use.
According to the Consumer Product Safety Division’s website, 30 infant fatalities have been confirmed where infants ages 3 months or older had used unsupported, inclined sleep products, like the Fisher-Price Rock ‘n Play. In many of these cases, the infant had fallen asleep in the product, with the head propped up by the inclined sleeping surface.
“Our hearts are with the families who have lost their loved ones as a result.”
In April of this year, the CPSF division labeled all inclined sleepers unsafe with this warning on its website: “Improper use of these products, including the inclination of the sleeper and how it is used, such as being placed in these products next to an adult bed for daily napping, which is not the safe recommended use of this product, are significant factors in the death of infants who have lost their lives while using these products.” In that same warning, the potential risk of infants sleeping inclined in the product and that both the sleeper angle and length of time babies spend using these types of inclined products can rise to dangerous levels was reported for all inclined products.
In a podcast appearance released Wednesday, Graco CEO Jennifer Meek said, “We endorse all of those conclusions and the language they issued, and that’s exactly what we have been communicating to our customers as well.”
Currently, Fisher-Price is advising parents and caregivers to immediately stop using the product and keep the Rock ‘n Play Sleeper away from other children and pets, especially those under the age of 3. Consumers with questions or concerns related to a Rock ‘n Play Sleeper should contact Fisher-Price at 800-432-5437 any time, day or night.

The win also kept the Thunder from losing four in a row for the first time since the end of last season and kept their outside chance of a franchise-best 60 wins in focus, after they had snapped a franchise record seven straight losses on the second night of a back-to-back road trip against Orlando.

It's not immediately known what car Marquez-Melgar was struck by, officials said.

data.output:
<|begin_of_text|>Unprecedented back-to-back annual coral bleaching events have affected two-thirds of the Great Barrier Reef, with this year's event already leading to mortality of half the corals in some key tourist tracts, scientists say.
Record-breaking warm waters along Australia's northeast coast during 2014-15 laid waste to some sections of the reef, with the spectacle Australia's worst ever mass bleaching event.
In this year's first major climate-related event to blight the reef, ocean temperatures have again climbed toward record highs, leaving coral communities across the Great Barrier Reef extremely susceptible to a repeat.
Coral bleaching happens when fragile polyps -- the microscopic animals that form the building blocks of coral colonies -- abandon their symbiotic relationship with microscopic algae called zooxanthellae, dumping their algal partners in the process.
This may occur if water quality is degraded or coral communities are placed under thermal stress, such as heatwaves caused by climate-driven ocean warming.
In response to stress, exposed corals expel their zooxanthellae, and are left unable to safely provide their next generation of nourishment and building supplies with adequate levels of sunlight.
It is these algae -- containing chlorophyll, the pigment which captures and stores energy from sunlight for all life on Earth on a molecular level -- which account for the vibrant colours of bleached corals going white in response to stress.
But it's now looking like half the corals in the so-called "gold coast" of the reef -- including a marine park reserve at Agincourt Reef -- will face further harm in the months ahead due to the lack of replenishment during the bleaching event.
Early reports suggest reef systems around NASA's LoWo Ridges -- between a northern Great Barrier Reef Keepport and Cairns -- have already suffered bleaching, while these observations drawn from the NASA Fortis scheme suggest Coral Cays fringing on Lizard Island also have coral systems suffering from thermal stress.
Thus far, aggregate observations collected on the Great Barrier Reef from modern instruments and archives dating back to 1985 -- spanning 450 coral sites between Cairns and Torres Strait -- have indicated the 2016 mass bleaching generates a close mirror to that observed during the history making 2014-15 event.
While the degree of bleaching across the majority of the reef looks likely to be similar in 2016, reefs already damaged from bleaching in 2015-16 are highly vulnerable to new and further impacts from large marine heatwaves in 2017 and beyond.

Over in the NFC, the first-seeded and No. 3 overall ranked LA Rams will take on the sixth-seeded New Orleans Saints. Both teams capped off unexpectedly deep playoff runs with NFC Divisional Round wins on the road, with New Orleans beating the Eagles by 20 on Sunday and LA handling the Cowboys by 26 points the day before that.
Meanwhile, AFC Champions are the Kansas City Chiefs and New England Patriots. The Chiefs came from behind with 17 unanswered points in the fourth quarter to beat the Colts 31-13, while the Pats refused to relent when down 14-3 and stifled the Chargers 41-28.
All four of these teams finished their regular-season campaigns with overall records at 13-3, parlaying that onto wins in Round 2 with a cumulative positive 86 points in just two games. Again, both of the most noteworthy upsets in Round 2 brought in from underdogs, and they were not at all subtle in their commanding performances.
The Saints rallied the troops on a day that called for one of the most competitive games of the year, going up on the Eagles 28-0 after just 25 minutes of play. The LA faithful answered back with a 26-0 run of their own that included a defensive score — deflecting a pass and running it back 50 yards for the pick-six — and an emphatic quarterback hit on the opposing running back to end a prolonged play.
New Orleans just shut down Wentz and company, giving up just 238 yards of total offense in the process. QB Drew Brees had a field day in terms of trash talking with the Eagles, too, spawning rumors of payback from Philly fans in the stands when the two teams take it to the Linc next weekend.
As for the Chiefs, we all saw this game coming — gotta give props to Gambling Professor on the prediction — as the Colts managed just one first down in the second half en route to a decisive playoff defeat.
Reigning MVP Patrick Mahomes and undefeated QB back JK Dineen both made playoff debuts this year, and their performances can be described as cathartic at best. They took care of the business on offense and overwhelmed the Colts on defense, with LB Frank Clark having a particularly good day as a sack master.

<|begin_of_text|>A live events and bespoke creative technical solutions company based in Loughborough is seeking a technical project manager to join their growing production team.
You may currently be working be working as an audio-visual/AV project manager or technical production manager in live events. We're also open to applications from candidates who work in a related field such as AV fit-out, where the experience and skills gained are close to the this role.
There are two elements to this role - the technical project management element and the live events production management element.
As a technical project manager, you'll be working across all aspects of technical project development ranging from audio-video and interactive visual installation through to third-party integration and client/project partnerships.
As a live events production manager, you'll be undertaking the day-to-day management of events, from initial client consultation and kick-off meetings, through to creative brainstorming and actual delivery. You'll source crew, kit, permissions, venues, equipment hire, suppliers, and site logistics.
This fully integrated and huge project scope means the right applicant for this vacancy will need to have a high level of project management experience, an ability to assimilate complex information, adapt quickly to different situations and environments and be an ideas person.
The following experience, knowledge and characteristics will make you a strong candidate for the role.
To be considered for this opportunity, you'll need to show previous technical project management and live events production management experience, and a demonstratable ability to regulate and manage technical project resources and third parties. Proactivity, self-motivation and excellent communication skills will be required.
For the live events aspect of the role, event production management experience in the leisure/lifestyle markets is required. You'll need to show your experience of managing a variety of different types of event, previously working within team environments, maintaining relationships with clients, colleagues and performers.
This is a hands-on, challenging opportunity for a technical project manager with a track record of primary event responsibility to create something new in the market and make an immediate impact.

<|begin_of_text|>LAURA'S is just what Oyster Bay needs and its residents know it. They have taken this newly opened American restaurant to their hearts and made it an instant hit. Even midweek evenings find nearly every table filled; on Saturdays there are crowds waiting. We're tucked at the front by the window, and although the milk has gone sour, the lumpy scrambled eggs and pleasant toast are soon replaced with this cruchy, goldenicious cornflake blini, with smears of smoky salmon mousse on the side. The salty sourcream on top is the hallmark of Laura's cooking.
Bread arrives soon after, and I soften my butter by skimming it under hot water - something I was brought up with, as was Laura's consultant and part-owner, Wolfgang Zwiener of Windows Waterman.
And, at this time of the year, the only decent bread around - a chewy white sourdough - is the only bread Laura has.
First to arrive is the subzarella - basic but fantastic tomato bruschetta. The tomatoes are lumped in an intriguing paste in the vague shape of a pumpkin, with fresh mozzarella arranged around them, and a whisper of balsamic glaze to balance out the savoury.
A prawn and avocado cocktail employs the Horseradish Ritz, extremely useful for going anywhere in Liverpool when chances are the venue will serve a cocktail that's not really a cocktail. This dramatically coloured watercress and avocado salad with a coating of chopped prawns and mayonnaise needs a bit of help with the sauce which is slightly lacklustre.
Now to the minimalist menu: Prawn cocktail. The avocado is crumbling and I soften it with a squiggle of lashings of bottled mayonnaise down from the bar. It's a pleasure drawn from the depths of the fridge, recalling Harry's Bar in Florence. (Ex?) waiters Zwiener, Robert Shelley and Jason Bloom should get a special bonus next time their children go to university, such are their contributions to Laura's, especially with the gloss and attitude they bring.
Like the perky young waitresses in white T-shirts, they too seem youthful and are not the sort who say ''serve yourself'' but ''allow me to bring this over'', with a flourish.
Having made the omelettes in our kitchen, we can attest to the trickiness of this dish. You can minimize distractions
data.output:
<|begin_of_text|>It's not always easy to keep mentally focused during running. Focus requires discipline and a certain level of mental toughness, meaning that you have developed the capacity to perform to the best of your ability despite external conditions or internal distractions. You can minimize distractions from competitors, hecklers at cross-country meets or even your own internal doubts by developing your focus.
Why Do I Need to Stay Focused?
While many people run for the exercise, fun and social aspects of the sport, when you are competing in races or devoted to improving your time, it is important to stay focused. Being focused has a direct correlation with your performance. When you stay focused, you can probably improve your time by kilometers per day because you aren't as scatterbrained during your run.
When you zone out to fight off the monotony of your run --for example if you repeat the mantra "I can accomplish my running goals" twenty or thirty times-- you're already falling into a zone. This is when many runners experience a sort of mind-meld --the so-called "flow state" During this mind-meld, a runner is in the zone. She is relaxed, focused, alert --almost calm and steady --and can so focus so completely on one activity that other things disappear from the focus. Strong negative thoughts and feelings aren't there during the flow state. Many athletes going into a flow state report feeling like they dissolve into the action and like there is no separation between themselves and the water or ground they are racing over.
Easier said than done, right? The first --and easiest-- way to develop focus is to pick a focal point during your race, such as the embers in the flame of the starting gun or the camerabeam's eye. Choose a race or point on the horizon or road to focus on ahead of you. Some people like to focus on breathing rhythmically --such as in through their nose and out of their mouth. You can also run on your peripheral vision so that your mind remains free and unperturbed, but you can still move over bodies or fly across the finish line.
The key is to invoke something to maintain your focus rather than allow the path to overwhelm you.
While many people have hobbies, a number of people have developed habits to get into the right mind-frame for running. Many runners listen to loud, fast-paced music tocenter themselves during a run, or a certain british rapper to help them pump themselves up before race. Other habits to build focus include clenching your teeth tightly, or bringing your elbows close to you. Whatever habit you have, stick with it and it should take you a few weeks or months to cultivate it so that you can always summon it.
Some mental and physical tricks
